The key insight here is that long division in base $5$ follows the same procedure as long division in base $10$. We can perform the division step by step, keeping in mind that each digit represents a power of $5$ instead of a power of $10$.
1. Set up the long division:
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & \\
   \cline{2-5}
   12 & 1 & 1 & 2 & 1 \\
   \end{array} $$

2. Divide $11$ by $12$ in base $5$. The quotient is $0$ with a remainder of $11$.
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 0 & \\
   \cline{2-5}
   12 & 1 & 1 & 2 & 1 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & \downarrow \\ \cline{2-4}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 1 & 1 &  \\
   \end{array} $$

3. Bring down the next digit, $2$, to get $112$.
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 0 & \\
   \cline{2-5}
   12 & 1 & 1 & 2 & 1 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & \downarrow \\ \cline{2-4}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 1 & 1 & 2 \\
   \end{array} $$

4. Divide $112$ by $12$ in base $5$. The quotient is $4$ with a remainder of $4$.
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 4 & \\
   \cline{2-5}
   12 & 1 & 1 & 2 & 1 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 1 & 0 & 3 \\ \cline{3-4}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 4 & 1 \\
   \end{array} $$

5. Bring down the last digit, $1$, to get $41$.
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 4 & \\
   \cline{2-5}
   12 & 1 & 1 & 2 & 1 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 1 & 0 & 3 \\ \cline{3-4}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 4 & 1 \\
   \end{array} $$

6. Divide $41$ by $12$ in base $5$. The quotient is $3$ with a remainder of $0$.
   $$
   \begin{array}{c|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 4 & 3 \\
   \cline{2-5}
   12 & 1 & 1 & 2 & 1 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{1} & 0 & 3 & \downarrow \\ \cline{2-4}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 4 & 1 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 4 & 1 \\ \cline{4-5}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & 0
   \end{array} $$

The solution approach is to expand the expression $(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a})$ using the distributive property of cross products. The cross product of a vector with itself is zero, which simplifies the expression. The given cross products of $\mathbf{a}$, $\mathbf{b}$, and $\mathbf{c}$ can be substituted to compute the final result.
1. Expand the expression $(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a})$ using the distributive property of cross products:

$$\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= 6 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 2 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - 3 \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a}
\end{align*}$$

2. Simplify the expression using the fact that the cross product of a vector with itself is zero:

$$\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= 6 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} - 2 \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} - 3 \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{0}
\end{align*}$$

3. Substitute the given cross products:

$$\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= 6 \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ - 7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} - 2 \begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ - 7 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} - 3 \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}$$

4. Compute the final result:

$$\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= \begin{pmatrix} -18 \\ -49 \\ 96 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}$$

The key insight in this solution is to use the double angle formula repeatedly to simplify the expression. By multiplying both sides of the equation by $\sin \frac{2 \pi}{7}$, we can apply the double angle formula to convert the product of cosines into a single cosine term. This process is repeated until we arrive at a simple expression that can be easily evaluated.
1. Let $x = \cos \frac{2 \pi}{7} \cos \frac{4 \pi}{7} \cos \frac{8 \pi}{7}$.
2. Multiply both sides of the equation by $\sin \frac{2 \pi}{7}$:
   $$\begin{align*}
   x \sin \frac{2 \pi}{7} &= \sin \frac{2 \pi}{7} \cos \frac{2 \pi}{7} \cos \frac{4 \pi}{7} \cos \frac{8 \pi}{7}
   \end{align*}$$
3. Apply the double angle formula to the right-hand side:
   $$\begin{align*}
   x \sin \frac{2 \pi}{7} &= \frac{1}{2} \sin \frac{4 \pi}{7} \cos \frac{4 \pi}{7} \cos \frac{8 \pi}{7}
   \end{align*}$$
4. Apply the double angle formula again:
   $$\begin{align*}
   x \sin \frac{2 \pi}{7} &= \frac{1}{4} \cos \frac{8 \pi}{7} \cos \frac{8 \pi}{7}
   \end{align*}$$
5. Simplify the right-hand side:
   $$\begin{align*}
   x \sin \frac{2 \pi}{7} &= \frac{1}{8} \sin \frac{16 \pi}{7}
   \end{align*}$$
6. Recognize that $\sin \frac{16 \pi}{7} = \sin \frac{2 \pi}{7}$:
   $$\begin{align*}
   x \sin \frac{2 \pi}{7} &= \frac{1}{8} \sin \frac{2 \pi}{7}
   \end{align*}$$
7. Divide both sides by $\sin \frac{2 \pi}{7}$ to solve for $x$:
   $$\begin{align*}
   x = \frac{1}{8}
   \end{align*}$$

